<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Unions warned on Labour links row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION leaders were warned yesterday that they risked damaging the Labour
party's reputation by opposing reforms of their links with the party urged
by Mr John Smith, its leader, Ralph Atkins writes.
As leaders of six of Britain's biggest unions prepared to meet later this
week to discuss tactics for opposing the move, Mr Roy Hattersley, former
deputy leader, warned that Labour would be 'cruelly handicapped' if it
continued to be regarded as being dominated by trade unions.
Labour party officials say Mr Smith is braced for a showdown with unions
over his plans to introduce one-member-one-vote for the selection and
re-selection of Labour parliamentary candidates. The row is expected to come
to a head at Labour's conference in October.
Ranged against Mr Smith are likely to be the Transport and General Workers'
union, the GMB general union, the MSF technicians' union, the UCW
communications union and RMT, the rail and seamen's union.
Mr Smith may also make the main Labour speech when the Commons debates the
principle of the Maastricht treaty's social chapter, probably later this
year.
Labour party strategists are considering the move as part of an effort to
increase the number of high-profile Commons appearances made by the Labour
leader.
Strategists feel the set-piece Commons speech remains Mr Smith's forte
rather than the thrust and counter-thrust of prime minister's questions.
</TEXT>
