<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Welsh deal angers Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DAVID HUNT, Welsh secretary, angered the Labour benches in the Commons
yesterday by confirming the existence of a written agreement between the
government and Welsh nationalist MPs over the membership of the European
Community's proposed committee of the regions.
Mr Ron Davies, the shadow Welsh secretary, said membership of the committee
 -to be established under the terms of the Maastricht treaty  - should be
determined at local government level.
To cheers, he told the minister: 'Any veto, any trickery or any
gerrymandering from you will be completely unacceptable'.
Challenging the Labour leadership to say in turn whether they supported the
Maastricht treaty, Mr Hunt stressed that without it there would be no
committee of the regions - 'and that would be a great shame for Wales'.
Mr Hunt also announced investment in Wales worth Pounds 15m, which he said
would create 425 jobs and safeguard a further 156.
He told MPs that the projects by eight companies setting up, modernising or
expanding operations in the principality were being backed by Pounds 2.6m in
Regional Selective Assistance from the Welsh Office.
Mr Hunt said the new investment was further proof that Wales was leading the
rest of Britain out of recession.
'It is the Welsh Dragon which is breathing fire into the UK recovery,' he
said.
But Labour's Mr Paul Flynn (Newport W) protested there had been no recovery
in Wales.
'What has happened is that a reasonably-paid, highly-skilled workforce has
been turned into a full-scale sweatshop,' he said.
</TEXT>
