<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tory Euro-sceptics plan tactics
after Danish poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY EURO-SCEPTICS were last night putting on a brave face ahead of today's
Danish referendum on Maastricht while acknowledging that the poll will
probably result in a Yes vote.
If the Danes do vote Yes, the Maastricht bill will return to the Commons for
its third reading on Thursday before moving on to the Lords. The government
is assured of a large majority in Thursday's vote largely because Labour has
decided to abstain.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, is expected to give an initial response
to the referendum in a speech tonight at a Confederation of British Industry
dinner. It is widely expected that a No vote would result in Thursday's
business being changed.
Some Euro-sceptics were yesterday keeping their spirits up by looking
forward to obstacles that the government still has to cross.
These include the bill's passage through the Lords and the possible judicial
review of the assertion by ministers that failing to incorporate the
protocol containing Britain's social chapter opt-out into UK law had no
effect on their ability to ratify the treaty.
Mrs Teresa Gorman, Tory MP for Billericay, forecast difficulties in store
for the government if a motion on a Maastricht referendum was selected for
debate at the Conservative party conference this autumn.
'If conference votes yes for a referendum, the government would have a hell
of a problem,' she said.
The Maastricht issue was 'by no means dead', Mrs Gorman added. 'We are not
talking about the vicarage tea party, after all, but the way this country is
governed.'
Others drew encouragement from the way the hard core of 26 Euro-sceptics has
held together for almost a year since the bill's second reading.
Still others were buoyed by a sense of having performed a valuable public
service with their opposition over Maastricht.
'There is a feeling among the group that we can say 'we told you not to
believe Neville Chamberlain,'' said one MP, en route to a prayer meeting
outside the Danish embassy.
Another prominent Euro-sceptic referred to the remarks made this weekend by
Sir Edward Heath and said he regarded it as the 'pinnacle' of his political
career to be told that he would be hated by the former prime minister.
In Thursday's vote, Euro-sceptic leaders will be aiming to beat their
'high-water mark' of 38 Tory rebels who defied the government last month by
supporting a Maastricht referendum. They say that some waverers may well be
tempted into their ranks by the virtual certainty of a government victory.
They plan to meet tomorrow to discuss the way forward. They are expected to
tell government whips not to count on their support on Europe-related issues
even after Maastricht has completed its Commons passage.
The government, meanwhile, is expected to take pains to minimise the
rebellion on Thursday.
One MP who supported a referendum but is not among the Euro-sceptic
hard-core said yesterday that he would vote with the government on the third
reading.
</TEXT>
