<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Second building society backs PIA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRADFORD and Bingley, the UK's seventh largest building society, has
welcomed plans to form the Personal Investment Authority, the controversial
self-regulatory body for retail financial services, Norma Cohen writes.
The endorsement by Bradford and Bingley, the only big building society to
remain a dispenser of independent financial advice, follows a similar
decision by Halifax, the market leader. Earlier this month it became the
first society to back the authority.
The authority is intended to bring all retail financial services providers,
including banks and building societies, under the umbrella of a single
self-regulatory body.
But in the authority's planning stages, banks and building societies had
baulked at joining, and life insurance companies had said they would not
join unless the banks did as well.
Mr Geoffrey Lister, Bradford and Bingley chairman, said: 'The PIA would
bring consistent rules and standards of supervision to the whole industry.'
</TEXT>
