<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / City divided on how to plug tide of price-sensitive leaks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Stock Exchange's public censure last Friday of London International
Group, the condoms to photo processing company, for leaking information was
well-timed. In Saturday's papers, alongside news of the censure, were
detailed reports that British Airways will today launch a rights issue.
The BA leak, if true, will embarrass the company because of its timing. But
it also suggests that the selective passing of price-sensitive information
from companies or their advisers to the market remains widespread.
LIG was censured after it separately told 13 analysts and four institutions
that profits forecasts for the company were too high. The exchange said this
type of information should have been released simultaneously to all
investors via an official announcement.
Most in the City would probably agree with the exchange in this case, and
concur that LIG's profit warning overstepped the rules. There is, however,
little agreement about how to deal with leaks generally.
Mr David Barclay, deputy head of corporate finance at County NatWest, said:
'We would welcome a tightening up of the application of equality of
information principle. But it is a grey area - this has always been a
difficult area.'
Another merchant banker, who did not want to be identified, said: 'It
happens all the time. You need to feed out little titbits, because if you
don't then you have a false market.'
The LIG case has focused attention on when leaks are price-sensitive and
therefore only disclosable through an official announcement. With the
government proposing tighter laws against insider trading it also raises the
question of whether companies should review the way they release information
to analysts and the press.
The exchange is reluctant to lay down guidelines for what is and is not
price-sensitive, saying it believes companies and their financial advisers
are better placed to judge. A decision by J Sainsbury to open two new stores
is less significant than a similar move by a much smaller company.
Equally, J Sainsbury's decision to expand is more significant than a similar
move by a company in an industry with long lead times, in process
engineering for example.
Companies and advisers talk of a 'grey area' of disclosure, which may have
been built up over years of practice. For example, hotel companies often
reveal publicly and privately their occupancy levels even though, especially
with smaller companies, these figures can be very price-sensitive.
In general, the exchange points to the 'Yellow Book' of listing rules,
requiring the immediate release of information which 'might reasonably be
expected to have a material effect' on a share price or trading volume. If
in doubt, according to the exchange, consult your financial adviser. The
relationship between companies and analysts is also likely to be reviewed
after the LIG ruling. In the past some companies have 'steered' analysts to
profit or loss figures. Some analysts admit that without this help, profit
forecasts soon become little better than guesswork.
The exchange said it agreed companies needed to have close relations with
analysts. But at private briefings no new material information should be
released, nor should precise profit or loss figures be revealed. Information
should not be sufficiently precise for analysts to work out exact figures.
Companies had probably already started tightening up in this area after the
conviction earlier this year of an Edinburgh fund manager for insider
dealing after he had been given a profits warning by a company in advance of
its publication.
According to the finance director of a FT-SE 100 company: 'These are
important developments and we need to make sure we are up with best
practice. We will have to be a little more careful.' With pressure on
companies and their advisers to stop leaking, official announcements are
likely to become more frequent and, perhaps, more thorough. Many companies
use announcements to communicate the outline of a development or change in
strategy. Detailed questions from analysts and journalists are then dealt
with at meetings or by telephone.
When the news is bad, companies have been reluctant to issue official
announcements, mainly because the market can overreact. As with LIG, many
have preferred to use leaking.
Mr John Makinson, of investor relations company Makinson Cowell, said that
if companies made more routine announcements through the exchange, there
would be less of a stigma attached to releasing bad news.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
