<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Accountancy ex-investigator to face probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FORMER head of the investigations committee of the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales has been called to appear before its
disciplinary committee.
The institute said yesterday that its disciplinary committee will study the
'supervisory responsibilities' carried out by Mr Brian Worth when he was in
charge of the investigations committee. He was also chairman of Clark
Kenneth Leventhal (CKL), an international association of accountancy firms.
The inquiry follows the conviction for forgery and deception at the Old
Bailey three years ago of Mr Nick Young, a former executive director of CKL
based in London.
The case has been referred to the disciplinary committee by the institute's
investigations committee, which has judged that there is a case to answer.
Mr Worth resigned from the investigations committee in late 1991 when it
began examining the case.
Mr Young, who was not an accountant, used CKL's address and its stationery
as part of a scheme which attracted more than Pounds 7m from more than 70
investors over 10 years.
While claiming to invest money in offshore trusts offering high rates of
return, Mr Young was actually spending it on a system of horserace betting
which he believed he had perfected while attending Cambridge University in
the 1960s.
Mr Richard Hornsby, the chairman of the CKL victims' group - which
represents those who gave money to Mr Young - said that he drew comfort from
the referral decision.
Five writs claiming Pounds 7m plus interest have already been issued. A
further writ for about Pounds 1m is expected shortly.
Mr Worth said yesterday that he also welcomed the proceedings as a chance to
clear his name.
He said that the CKL committee was spread around the world and that Mr Young
was the association's only employee in the UK. He said that he had only met
Mr Young once or twice each month.
More than 60 CKL investors are pressing ahead with legal action for
compensation against CKL and Clark Whitehill, its British associate member.
A hearing for the action is scheduled for the end of the year.
The institute's disciplinary committee is expected to meet to hear Mr
Worth's case in September.
</TEXT>
