<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Attack on bank chief's pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER WOOD, the direc-tor of Royal Bank of Scotland who is expected to
earn at least Pounds 10m this year, was accused by employees yesterday of
accepting money that could have preserved some of the 3,500 jobs being shed
by the bank.
Criticism of Mr Wood's pay as chief executive of Royal Bank's Direct Line
insurance subsidiary coincided yesterday with attacks at the annual
conference of the Banking, Insurance and Finance Union in Llandudno on the
jobs policies of banks and building societies.
Mr Ian Williams, a member of the union's national executive, accused Mr Wood
of betraying Royal Bank employees who face job losses over the next five
years as part of the bank's branch restructuring project, called Columbus.
'It may be that some of the jobs are going in order to pay Mr Wood's bonus,'
Mr Williams said. 'If that is so, then the going rate for the job seems a
bit high. Even Judas was only paid 30 pieces of silver to betray one man.'
Delegates expressed worry about large job losses in the finance industry.
The union estimates that 70,000 jobs have gone in the past three years and
that 30,000 more are at at risk.
Royal Bank was singled out for criticism because of its refusal to rule out
compulsory redundancies. The union has just reached an agreement with
National Westminster Bank which it believes will reduce compulsory
redundancies.
Bifu said yesterday it expected the Co-operative Bank to breach an agreement
on job security by making up to 20 managers compulsorily redundant after
meetings this week. The union said a further 130 clerical staff risked
losing their jobs after being designated 'surplus staff', although the bank
had given a commitment that they would not be made compulsorily redundant
this year.
</TEXT>
