<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Midlands tram contract awarded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CENTRAM, a company formed by construction group Taylor Woodrow and rail
equipment maker Ansaldo Trasporti of Naples, was yesterday chosen by the
West Midlands Passenger Transport Authority to build and operate the first
line of a local tram system, Paul Cheeseright writes.
Centram will pay Pounds 10m towards the building costs and will receive a
franchise to operate the regional light rail rapid transit system without
subsidy for 20 years.
The capital cost of the project at April prices is Pounds 112m, leaving
Centram and Centro, the operating arm of the passenger transport authority,
to find Pounds 102m before construction starts.
The total cost, including land purchase and an allowance for inflation
during the projected three-year construction period, is Pounds 135m.
Midland Metro will run 20km from central Birmingham, via West Bromwich and
Bilston, to Wolverhampton, using mainly existing railway trackbeds. Only in
Wolverhampton will the line run along the street.
Centro hopes construction will start in 1994-95. 'The only impediment to it
going forward is finding a slot in government spending plans,' said Mr Bob
Tarr, its director- general.
By selecting a private sector partner, Centro hopes to take advantage of the
government's readiness, expressed in the Autumn Statement, to look
favourably on private-sector or public-sector plans for infrastructure
developments. It needs Pounds 50m from the Department of Transport.
At present the government's budget of about Pounds 50m a year for regional
light rail projects is being spent in Sheffield. The west Midlands project
is said to be the next in line.
The balance would come from local authority borrowing, once the government
is prepared to give credit approvals, and from the EC.
</TEXT>
