<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Lloyd's deputy to quit syndicate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Stephen Merrett, deputy chairman of Lloyd's of London, is to stand down
as the active underwriter of syndicate 418, one of the insurance market's
largest syndicates, at the start of next year.
Mr Merrett, 53, will spend more time on the development of activities of
Merrett Holdings and will be especially concerned with attracting
incorporated capital to the group.
As deputy chairman of Lloyd's he will also form a reinsurance company to
isolate liabilities from old US asbestosis and pollution claims.
Mr Merrett will be replaced at syndicate 418 by his current deputy, Mr
Barnabas Hurst-Bannister. A statement by Merrett Holdings said: 'The matter
of Mr Stephen Merrett's succession and role within the group has been under
consideration for some time.'
Meanwhile, an out-of-court settlement of some of the legal actions troubling
the Lloyd's of London insurance market appeared to be still a possibility
yesterday following a meeting between Mr Peter Middleton, chief executive,
and leaders of four groups of loss-making Names - the individuals whose
assets back the insurance market.
'We are at the foothills of a Mount Everest of negotiations,' said Mr
Michael Deeny, chairman of the Gooda Walker Action Group, one of four action
group leaders at the meeting. He said Mr Middleton was 'making a determined
and serious effort, but a deal will be difficult to achieve'.
Also at the two-hour meeting were Mr Colin Hook, Mr Alan Porter and Sir
David Berriman, chairmen respectively of the representatives of Feltrim
Names Association, the Devonshire Names Action Group and the Rose Thomson
Young Action Group.
The groups represent a majority of Names who sustained heavy losses from
spiral reinsurance, in which syndicates and companies reinsured each others'
exposure to high-level catastrophe loss.
Insurance companies which sell policies directly to the public by telephone
are poised to double their share of the Pounds 6.1bn UK motor insurance
market over the next five years, according to a survey by the London-based
GSR group.
It estimates that 'direct writers' will sell two in every five motor
insurance policies by 1998. In 1992 the three biggest direct writers -
Direct Line, Churchill and The Insurance Service - spent Pounds 5.6m on
advertising, just under 25 per cent of the industry's total.
</TEXT>
