<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Call to scrap eight councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EIGHT councils in Derbyshire should be abolished by 1995-96, the Local
Government Commission for England said yesterday.
The commission suggested in Alfreton that the current county council and
nine district councils should be replaced by two councils - one for the city
of Derby and the other for the rest of Derbyshire - with administrative
savings estimated at Pounds 16m a year, or 9 per cent of the average council
tax bill.
The commission is examining ways of replacing the two-tier system of local
government with unitary authorities. It has made recommendations for
reorganisation in the Isle of Wight and Cleveland-Durham.
Reorganisation in Derbyshire has a particular significance because the
Labour-controlled county council was a political bete noire of the Thatcher
government.
Under the proposals, the authorities in Amber Valley, Bolsover, North East
Derbyshire, Chesterfield, Derbyshire Dales, High Peak, Erewash and South
Derbyshire would cease to exist. Derby City Council would retain its current
boundaries.
Although the proposals had been widely predicted, there were protests from
authorities with an uncertain future. Derbyshire Dales said: 'The worst
possible scenario for all the people of Derbyshire.'
South Derbyshire said: 'People in South Derbyshire will not stand by to
watch their district fall into oblivion.'
The commission will now test Derbyshire public opinion, 'to tailor local
government to the wishes of the people,' said Sir John Banham, chairman of
the commission.
It will present its final recommendation to the Department of Environment in
September.
</TEXT>
