<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / US and Russia in Bosnian initiatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US and Russia are taking new initiatives to try to breathe life into the
peace process in Bosnia, spurred on by the Bosnian Serbs' expected rejection
of the international peace plan in their referendum last weekend.
Croats and Moslems, meanwhile, fought savage street battles yesterday in the
Bosnian town of Mostar, which was rocked by a big explosion, possibly an
ammunition dump.
Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, said the way had been cleared
for a new round of discussions between the US and its allies, 'some of whom
have been wanting to hold up until after the referendum'. Consultations with
US allies would be held by phone over the next few days.
But he said he had no plans to go to New York on Friday for a UN Security
Council foreign ministers' meeting, being sought by Russia. The meeting, if
held, would discuss UN peacekeeping projects, but the US fears it would
underline the world's failure to agree on what to do next about Bosnia.
Though the Bosnian Serb referendum results are not expected until tomorrow,
Mr Christopher appeared to assume overwhelming rejection of the Vance-Owen
peace plan.
The US consultations about Bosnia coincide with a peace mission by Mr Andrei
Kozyrev, Russia's foreign minister. He went to Berlin yesterday for talks
with Mr Klaus Kinkel, his German counterpart, and is due to meet Croatian,
Bosnian and Serbian leaders in Split and Belgrade, starting today.
Mr Kozyrev said last night: 'We won't let a few militants and warlords stop
the international community from extinguishing the war in Bosnia.'
The international mediators, Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, will
also fly to the former Yugoslavia today for talks with the Croatian and
Bosnian presidents.
Mr Vitaly Churkin, Russia's special envoy to the peace talks, was much more
optimistic than his western counterparts about the Bosnian situation, when
announcing Mr Kozyrev's mission in Moscow yesterday.
'It is our view that there are not so many hardliners among the Bosnian
Serbs and they will be further isolated,' he told journalists. Serbia's
'very clear stand' for a peaceful settlement, and its blockade of supplies
to the Bosnian Serbs, except food and medicine, would change their minds
about the peace plan.
Mr Churkin reiterated Moscow's proposal that the Vance-Owen plan should be
implemented by the international community by stages.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, yesterday apologised for his
army chief, General Ratko Mladic, who threatened bomb attacks in western
cities, particularly London, if the west intervened in Bosnia. 'That was an
irresponsible and emotional reaction,' Mr Karadzic said.
Britain dismissed Gen Mladic's remarks as 'bombast and bluster'.
Croatian radio claimed that the big explosion in Mostar yesterday was caused
by a Moslem ammunition dump, which went up 'with tragic consequences'.
Moslem-controlled radio reported the historic centre was in flames after the
explosion. It accused Croat artillery of levelling the city centre. 'Several
ancient objects have been utterly destroyed. The medieval bridge, listed as
a world heritage by Unesco, was severely damaged.'
</TEXT>
