<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Bank governor to accept salary freeze for five years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR EDDIE GEORGE, the new governor of the Bank of England and a man wedded to
low inflation, has agreed to freeze his salary of more than Pounds 200,000
for his five-year period of office.
The Bank said yesterday that it knew of no one else in Britain who had shown
similar restraint over pay. 'We hope Mr George will start a new trend,' it
said.
Mr George, the present deputy governor who takes over the top job on July 1,
is known within Threadneedle Street as 'the last Stalinist' because of his
tough, autocratic management style.
He is convinced Britain must curb price and wage pressures if it is to
create a sound economy in the 1990s, a message to be rammed home today in
the Bank's new quarterly report on inflation.
The five-year freeze indicates that Mr George is anxious to avoid a repeat
of the row two years ago when news emerged of a 17 per cent pay rise agreed
by Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the current governor. At that time, he was
urging low wage increases as part of the battle against inflation.
Mr George, who has been at the Bank for 31 years, is thought to have agreed
on a salary of between Pounds 200,000 and Pounds 220,000 from the start of
his time in office.
The salary - the same as the amount paid to Mr Leigh-Pemberton last year -
is considerably more than that earned by other public servants, but well
below the pay of many top names in the City.
Mr George, aged 54, earned Pounds 164,910 in the year to February last year.
The Bank refuses to say how much Mr George is earning. He is reputed,
however, to have turned down in recent years a number of Pounds 1m
annual-salary jobs from big financial services companies.
The news about Mr George failed to impress the Banking, Insurance and
Finance Union, which called yesterday for the Bank to open pay talks for its
4,500 members there. It also rejected the government's public-sector pay
norm of 1.5 per cent.
Mr Jim Lowe, the union's assistant secretary for the Bank, said staff
deserved 'a decent pay rise' as much as the governor. 'A pay freeze is
easier to bear when your salary is over Pounds 200,000,' said Mr Lowe.
He said Bank of England staff had not achieved the scale of increases
received in recent years by the present governor.
In the year to February 1992, Mr Leigh-Pemberton, who is retiring after 10
years as governor, earned Pounds 164,311. He waived a further Pounds 34,135.
In the previous year he was paid Pounds 155,019 and in the 12 months to
February 1990 he earned Pounds 132,558.
RBS chief criticised Page 6
Editorial Comment Page 17
</TEXT>
