<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Sugar unrepentant in Spurs stand-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BATTLE between the two key shareholders at Tottenham Hotspur hotted up
over the weekend with details emerging of why Mr Alan Sugar, the chairman,
wants to sack Mr Terry Venables, the chief executive.
Mr Venables, who owns 22 per cent of the company, is fighting the attempt to
dismiss him. On Friday, just hours after being sacked, he obtained a High
Court injunction reinstating him as chief executive until a hearing on May
25.
Reasons for the attempted dismissal, according to the Sugar camp, included
Mr Venables' commercial activities at the club - which he was described as
pursuing 'almost relentlessly', sometimes without reference to Mr Sugar.
It also emerged that Mr Sugar, the electronics millionaire who owns 48 per
cent of Tottenham, had offered to buy Mr Venables' stake at the price he
paid for it. 'My offer was fair, even generous,' Mr Sugar said yesterday.
Mr Venables, who has invested about Pounds 3m in the club, buying most of
his shares at 75p, has described the offer as derisory. If he received only
Pounds 3m, that would be less than the Pounds 3.2m market value of the stake
at Friday's closing price of 89p and it would also mean a loss on his
financing costs. He borrowed most of the Pounds 3m he invested.
</TEXT>
