<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / International Company News: Alps Electric plunges to Y1.95bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALPS Electric, which supplies parts to consumer and other electronics
manufacturers, saw pre-tax profits fall to Y1.95bn (Dollars 17.5m) for the
year to March 1993.
This compared with Y7.02bn in the previous year, and was due to the fall in
both corporate and consumer spending.
The company expected difficult conditions to continue and forecast that it
would only break even at the pre-tax level and fall into net loss in the
current year.
The decline came largely as a result of the weakness in the Japanese and
European markets, Alps said. In Japan, production in the electronics
industry fell by 12 per cent, according to industry estimates.
Alps' sales fell 14 per cent to Y292bn from Y339bn while net profits are
expected to fall 78 per cent to Y600m.
Sales of electronic parts to colour TV and VTR manufacturers were
particularly weak, falling 25 per cent, followed by a 21 per cent fall in
sales to audio manufacturers.
Sales to the information and telecommunications industries were depressed at
home but it was helped by increased sales to the US and saw overall sales
decline just 1.7 per cent.
Alps said that while the electronics industry's inventory adjustments had
been more or less completed, full-scale recovery was not likely in the near
future as consumer spending was still at a low level.
The pressures of the yen's appreciation were also expected to impact
negatively on this year's earnings.
The company is forecasting a 4 per cent decline in sales to Y280bn and a net
loss of Y1.5bn in the current year.
Taiyo Fishery, the large fishing company, forecast an increase in pre-tax
profits for the year to Y1bn against a Y1.8bn loss in the previous year.
</TEXT>
