<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / BT unveils plans to sell BSkyB satellite TV dishes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Telecom plans to make its first move into the fast-growing home
entertainment market later this year, by selling dishes to receive BSkyB
broadcasts from the Astra television satellite.
Entertainment is potentially the biggest avenue of diversification for BT,
under increasing pressure from competitors such as cable TV companies, in
its traditional telephone and business communication markets. However, the
terms of its licence bar BT from providing entertainment channels on its
network.
BT is in the final stages of negotiation with two electronics companies to
manufacture satellite dishes and associated equipment in the UK. They will
go on sale in BT's shops and 'selected high street outlets' this autumn.
The move will throw BT's marketing muscle behind BSkyB, in which Pearson,
owner of the Financial Times, has a significant stake. BT and BSkyB are
believed to be discussing a deal that would give each access to the other's
customers.
The move would also provide powerful new competition for Amstrad, Mr Alan
Sugar's company, which so far has been the largest UK supplier of satellite
dishes and receivers. BT is unlikely to undercut Amstrad's prices
significantly but it is expected to compete on what it believes is a
superior record for product and service reliability.
According to the FT Satellite Monitor about 3.2m homes in the UK can now
receive satellite TV - at least 2m through their own dish and the remainder
by cable or community aerial.
UK sales of dishes and associated equipment are worth about Pounds 120m a
year, not a large target for a company of BT's size. But BT wants to use it
as a way into the huge new market emerging through the three-way
'convergence' of entertainment, telecommunications and computing.
Other signs of BT's ambitions are its home videophone, launched last month,
and recent agreements with US and European electronics companies to develop
personal computers with 'multimedia' facilities.
The experience gained from selling and servicing satellite dishes and any
associated marketing agreement with BSkyB would be useful preparation for
the time when BT is permitted to use its fast-expanding fibre optic network
for television.
Recent discoveries in optical electronics make it possible to send millions
of telephone calls down a single glass strand as a thin as a hair. As a
result, the network is likely to have a vast excess capacity  - and some BT
executives would like to use it for new forms of entertainment.
</TEXT>
