<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Tories poised to end secrecy on finances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONSERVATIVE party, which has a Pounds 19m deficit, may publish a
balance sheet this summer for the first time.
The move follows pressure from both Labour and the 'Charter' group of Tory
activists for removal of the secrecy surrounding the party's finances.
It comes as Mr Asil Nadir's flight to Cyprus and allegations - since
categorically denied - of the existence of offshore 'slush funds' have
revived criticism of the party's fundraising.
A meeting today of the party's newly constituted board of management is
likely to approve publication of a balance-sheet to bring greater openness
to its accounting.
The current proposals stop short of advocating a breakdown of individual
donations to the party, but should result in the 1992-93 accounts being the
most complete ever. 'The report will try to give as clear a view of the
party's finance as possible,' according to Mr Paul Judge, the party's
recently installed director-general.
The proposals reflect a comprehensive overhaul of the party's internal
accounting. In the past, the party has published a limited set of annual
accounts showing income and expenditure but not full figures on assets and
liabilities.
On fundraising, Sir Norman Fowler, the party chairman, is keen to guard
against future embarrassment by ensuring it is stressed to donors that there
can be no direct link between policy-making and their interests.
Central Office coffers have been hit by the party's falling-out with
prominent landowner donors over leasehold reform, and the recession's effect
on many companies.
Officers also acknowledge that much of the cash going to campaigners for a
Maastricht referendum might otherwise have come to the party.
Nonetheless, Mr Judge said the party was on course to meet its financial
targets, which call for its accumulated deficit to be wiped out by 1996. It
will soon announce that this deficit rose to Pounds 19m at the end of March
1993.
Mr Judge laughed off 'slush fund' allegations as 'completely untrue', saying
the party has 'offered a 10 per cent finder's fee to anyone who can come up
with the Pounds 200m'.
The Charter group will this week publish its own version of the 1992-93
accounts which it says gives a more accurate picture of the party's
finances.
</TEXT>
