<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Pressure mounts for U-turn on rail sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is coming under intense pressure to follow last week's
U-turns over school-tests and fines with new climbdowns on rail
privatisation and the collection of pension payments from post offices.
With prime minister John Major attempting to reassert his authority after
this month's disastrous election results, the government is facing a
determined effort to change its rail privatisation bill, spearheaded by a
group of Tory backbenchers.
It is also under pressure to back away from proposals which might compel
some pensioners to have pension payments made by automated credit transfers.
The Treasury is thought to be keen for more benefits to be paid in this way
rather than being collected over the counter from post offices. Mr Major
said last week that the government aimed to 'encourage' bank transfers while
maintaining a 'viable' network of Post Offices.
Mr Major acknowledged in his speech to last week's Scottish Conservative
Conference that - with its Commons majority down to 18 - the government
might be forced into an occasional climbdown. 'We may have to tack a little
here, manoeuvre a little there. That's politics,' he said.
The government is also facing the difficult prospect of piloting a long and
complicated finance bill through its committee stage without having its
revenue-raising proposals diluted.
Ministers, after facing down attempts to amend its proposed reform of the
North Sea tax regime and weathering a mini-rebellion over imposing value
added tax on domestic fuel, are concerned that proposed changes to the
company-car tax system could provide another potential flashpoint.
The MPs backing changes to the government's rail privatisation plans intend
to table a series of amendments to the bill for consideration at its Commons
report stage next week.
Among the likely amendments is one that would permit British Rail to bid
against the private sector for rail franchises. Others would seek to ensure
that Travelcards and senior citizens' railcards would not be axed.
Sir Keith Speed, the Tory MP for Ashford, said yesterday that the proposals
were designed to make rail privatisation 'popular and workable.' None of
them would undermine the principle of the bill, he said. Warning that if the
government demonstrated no flexibility MPs would have to 'consider our
position', he said that his 'strong hope' was for ministers to decide they
could accommodate the changes.
Mr Tim Rathbone, the Tory MP for Lewes, said the changes were 'in no way'
wrecking amendments.
</TEXT>
