<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Citizen's Charter cuts BR payouts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MONEY paid to British Rail passengers whose trains are late or cancelled has
been cut by more than half since the introduction of the Passenger's
Charter.
Latest figures confirm predictions that the charter would leave passengers
no better off than they were under the previous arbitrary and unpublicised
refund scheme.
BR says it has not yet calculated how much compensation has been paid since
the charter came into operation, but estimates the figure at a little more
than Pounds 3m a year.
In 1991, the last full year before the charter, BR paid out Pounds 7m -
although that figure was boosted by disruption to services caused by what BR
dubbed the 'wrong kind of snow'.
Before the Passenger's Charter came into force in May 1992, local managers
had discretion to hand out cash or travel vouchers when passengers wrote to
complain about unpunctuality or poor service.
The charter imposed a more rigid system of compensation. For example, trains
had to be more than an hour late before refunds could be claimed, and the
entitlement consisted of a voucher worth only 20 per cent of the fare.
When the Passenger's Charter was introduced, BR estimated that compensation
would soar to Pounds 10m-Pounds 15m a year. The Consumers' Association said:
'What the latest figures show more than anything else is that the
performance targets were too soft.'
The association said it had also had reports that BR was interpreting the
charter too rigidly, taking the guidelines as maximum levels of entitlement
instead of minimum ones. It called on BR to 'go with the spirit of the
charter rather than the letter'.
</TEXT>
