<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Radio 1 promotion policy is defended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC yesterday rejected claims from commercial stations that Radio 1 was
breaching its licence by running extensive promotions with the record
industry and other companies.
'There are strict guidelines about retaining editorial control, and we are
completely clean,' the BBC said, although it admitted that Radio 1 'pushed
to the limits of the guidelines'.
The Association of Independent Radio Companies has written to the BBC and
the Department of National Heritage claiming that outside companies have
spent Pounds 1m a year on promotions with Radio 1 in return for publicity
about their products.
Commercial stations claim the promotions are a form of cross-subsidisation,
with money earned through them being used to finance other BBC programmes.
Radio 1 said yesterday none of its promotions violated its licence and
denied the allegations of cross-subsidisation.
The BBC said on-air promotions, such as competitions to win trips to meet
bands, were 'editorially valid' and always involved popular bands which
would be receiving Radio 1 airplay in any case - although the station
admitted that the bands' records were likely to be played when a competition
was promoted.
</TEXT>
