The association said it had also had reports that BR was interpreting the
charter too rigidly, taking the guidelines as maximum levels of entitlement
instead of minimum ones. It called on BR to 'go with the spirit of the
charter rather than the letter'.
Another factor in the low level of payouts is believed to be a reluctance
among passengers to go to the trouble of submitting claims for trifling
levels of compensation. BR says most passengers are far more concerned about
improvements in performance than about claiming refunds.
Complaints about rail punctuality from passengers travelling to and from the
west of England have risen by 80 per cent, the Western England Transport
Users Consultative Committee says.
The number of passengers complaining to the committee in 1992-93 totalled
587 - a 20 per cent rise on 1991-92.
