<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Managers find block on career progress
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of upwards career moves made by managers has declined by nearly
40 per cent since a peak in 1987, the Institute of Management says.
In contrast, horizontal or downwards moves have doubled since 1980, Diane
Summers writes. The institute says assumptions about 'onward and upwards'
management careers may have to be dropped and managers adapt to sideways or
even downward moves. But managers change jobs more frequently than in the
early 1980s.
The institute carried out a survey of more than 800 of its members' careers
over the past 13 years. It found about 21 per cent changed their jobs each
year from 1980 to 1982, while 29 per cent changed jobs in 1992.
The reasons behind the moves have also changed, with those voluntarily
choosing different jobs dropping sharply. Enforced moves - particularly
redundancies and changes resulting from company restructuring - are now the
main type.
The study says it is not possible to link the most recent changes in
managers' careers directly to the recession. Instead, changing patterns
might reflect longer-term changes resulting from company restructuring. The
Institute of Personnel Management today warns companies to tackle age
discrimination voluntarily 'before social pressures force legislation to
outlaw discrimination against older workers'. The institute says the
recession has made the position worse.
Are Career Ladders Disappearing? Institute of Management, Management House,
Cottingham Road, Corby, Northants NN17 1TT. Free. Age and Employment. IPM
Camp Road, London SW19 4UX. Members Pounds 28; non-members Pounds 35.
</TEXT>
