<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / A firm voice in Threadneedle St: Profile of a man likely to
take a tough line in dealings with the Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF YOU sneak into the Bank of England tomorrow afternoon you will catch in
full flight the man whose views are one of the firmest elements in a
distinctly wobbly UK economic policy.
Professor Mervyn King, the Bank's economics director, will be launching its
quarterly report on inflation, a document written largely by him. It is seen
as a vital check on government ministers over possible price pressures now
Britain is outside the European exchange rate mechanism.
The 45-year-old professor is a principal lieutenant to Mr Eddie George, who
moves from Bank deputy governor to governor in July. Both men are determined
that Threadneedle Street shall play a bigger role in advising the Treasury
on monetary policy, a goal that may be helped by the Treasury's weakened
state in the aftermath of the ERM fiasco and a run of policy errors.
Prof King, who went to the Bank only two years ago, does not lack ambition.
One theory is that if the new and untried deputy governor - Mr Rupert
Pennant-Rea, former editor of the Economist - fails to make a mark then Prof
King would be his natural replacement.
The affable but publicity-shy Prof King enjoys a high reputation among
academics. Professor James Meade, the Nobel prize-winning economist, calls
him 'first-rate'; Mr Lawrence Summers, an ex-Harvard economist who is
under-secretary for international affairs at the US Treasury, says he is one
of the 'top few European economists' of his generation.
Prof King joined the Bank from the London School of Economics. A specialist
in taxation and corporate behaviour, he made a particular impression in the
US, where he has had several spells at Harvard and at Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
Prof King - educated at Wolverhampton Grammar School and King's College,
Cambridge - can be very eloquent. Professor Charles Goodhart of the LSE, a
former Bank economist, says: 'A big strength is that he can argue his case
at almost any level of academic complexity.'
But in the City he is viewed as an enigma. One City economist says:
'Meetings with Bank people are rarely a bundle of laughs but even so Mervyn
can be especially daunting; he is seen as unapproachable.'
Prof King can also be difficult to work for and, according to one Bank
economist, is 'a stickler for detail'. He once told his Bank staff to tear
up a speech the day before he was due to deliver it because he disagreed
with the fine print.
Another associate says: 'He's not the world's best diplomat; he's a bright
lad who makes it clear if he thinks people are not on his intellectual
plane.' A few weeks ago MPs on a Commons committee visibly bristled when he
suggested they might have trouble following his argument.
A certain robustness has also been evident in his dealings with the
Treasury, traditionally the senior partner in the monetary relationship.
Prof King is determined that the Bank's inflation report - the first of
which came out only in February - should be seen as the Bank's work,
untainted by Treasury influence. According to one account he told Treasury
officials to 'get stuffed' earlier this year when they tried to engineer
amendments to the first report.
Had he accepted the blandishments five years ago of former chancellor Lord
Lawson, Prof King might now be at the Treasury himself. He was offered the
job of deputy chief economic adviser - it would almost certainly have led to
being chief economist - but opted to stay in academic life.
Several people close to the professor believe academia may still reclaim
him. Harvard professor of economics John Kain says: 'Prof King did a great
job when he was here. Just about every leading US institute would bid should
he want to come back.'
</TEXT>
