<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Companies told to tackle age bias
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INSTITUTE of Personnel Management today warns companies to tackle age
discrimination voluntarily 'before social pressures force legislation to
outlaw discrimination against older workers'.
A survey of more than 1,000 members found that 80 per cent thought age
discrimination was a problem in UK companies. The institute says that the
recession has made the position worse.
An even greater proportion of members - 86 per cent - thought there should
be either legislation or a government-sponsored voluntary code of practice
to prevent the specification of age ceilings in job advertisements.
A separate survey, conducted earlier this year by Industrial Relations
Services, the independent research group, found that almost a third of job
advertisments specified an age bar - up from a quarter four years ago. Four
out of five advertisers giving a preference wanted someone under 45.
The government has so far ruled out the kind of anti-discrimination
legislation found in North America and France. The institute itself is
opposed to introducing laws, but its code of guidance recommends companies
not to specify ages in job advertisements.
The study finds that personnel managers themselves held some stereotyped
views about older workers: 66 per cent thought they were less able to accept
new technology, 63 per cent thought they were less able to adapt to change,
and 48 per cent thought they learnt less quickly.
Age and Employment. IPM Camp Road, London SW19 4UX. Members Pounds 28;
non-members Pounds 35.
