<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Bank may use new measure of money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England is considering a change to its way of measuring monetary
growth in the economy following widespread dissatisfaction with existing
measures of the money supply.
An article in the Bank's quarterly bulletin, published tomorrow, concludes
that a 'divisia' measure of money might have a closer relationship with
total expenditure in the economy than conventional monetary aggregates.
A divisia index weights each of its components - such as cash and bank and
building society deposits - according to the extent to which they represent
money for spending rather than saving. Existing money supply measures simply
add together the components without weighting.
The article points out that if the weights reflect the ease and cost with
which money - cash, low-interest deposits or high-interest deposits - can be
used for spending, the index will be more closely related to total
expenditure.
Broad money supply measures have been criticised for their failure to
provide a reliable indicator of the relationship between the level of money
in the economy and future inflation.
In spite of doubts about the accuracy of broad monetary aggregates, the
government reintroduced a monitoring range for M4 - notes and coins in
circulation plus bank and building society deposits - in October last year
as part of its strategy to control inflation following Britain's departure
from the European exchange rate mechanism. The monitor range for M4 is 3-9
per cent.
The government also watches M0, mainly notes and coins in circulation, which
has a monitor range of 0-4 per cent.
The Bank says that treating cash in the same way as interest-bearing
deposits is probably misleading. A divisia index, with weighted components,
would 'provide a measure of the total quantity of money held in the economy
for transaction purposes as opposed to savings purposes'.
The government should not hesitate to cut interest rates again if recession
in continental Europe starts to threaten the UK's recovery, according to
Oxford Economic Forecasting, the UK consultancy. Its latest assessment of
economic prospects, published today, says GDP will grow by 1.7 per cent this
year and 2.9 per cent next year.
It says fiscal policy should be tightened immediately to create room for
lower interest rates as those on the Continent come down. Tax increases set
out in the March Budget did not go far enough, OEF says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
