<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 93 / Prodi's return to Iri underlines sell-off plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE APPOINTMENT at the weekend of Professor Romano Prodi as chairman of Iri
is being viewed as a strong signal of the Italian government's intention to
push ahead with privatisation of the state holding company.
The appointment followed the arrest of Iri's chairman, Mr Franco Nobili, on
Wednesday on charges of corruption.
Mr Luigi Abete, the head of Confindustria, the industrialists' association,
welcomed the appointment of Prof Prodi, who resumes the post he left little
more than three years go.
Mr Abete said it represented clear evidence of a desire to 'accelerate the
process of privatisation'. Iri's 1992 losses are believed to be more than
L4,200bn (Pounds 1.8bn) and group debts are a staggering L70,000bn.
Mr Nobili is still being held in Milan's San Vittore jail as magistrates
investigate allegations that he was involved in arranging kick-backs on
contracts for two power stations both while he was heading Iri and in his
previous role as chief executive of Cogefar, the private construction group.
The quick substitution of Mr Nobili bore the stamp of the decisiveness of
prime minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, the former governor of the Bank of
Italy, who last month was called in under crisis conditions to head the
government.
Prof Prodi had been a strong front-runner as an independent candidate to
head the new government. He was even called to Rome from his native Bologna
under the impression he was the next premier. But the Socialist party
objected at the last minute to his candidature.
Prof Prodi, who is close to the Christian Democrats, headed Iri from 1982 to
1989. Another economist, Prof Franco Reviglio, was brought in to run Eni,
the state oil concern and the other large public sector group. Mr Giulio
Andreotti, then prime minister, had him replaced by Mr Nobili, marking a
return to more politicised management at Iri.
A firm believer in slimming down Iri, which accounts for more than 5 per
cent of GDP, Prof Prodi was frequently frustrated by political interference.
He tried unsuccessfully to privatise SME, the foodstuffs and distribution
group, and pushing this sell-off will now be one of his first tasks.
Iri desperately needs to raise cash through divestiture to meet pressing
financial commitments. Apart from SME, Prof Prodi is expected to turn his
immediate attention to the delays in proposals for Iri to move out of
banking through the sale of its stake in the commercial banks Credito
Italiano and Banca di Roma.
The advent of Prof Prodi raises questions about the future role of Mr
Michele Tedeschi, the chief executive.
