<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 93 / Japanese offer tariff cuts to revive trade talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN HAS offered to cut customs tariffs on 770 industrial products as part
of a new effort by leading industrial countries to breathe life into the
Uruguay Round of multinational trade negotiations.
Mr Yoshiri Mori, trade minister, announced the offer at an all-day meeting
in Toronto yesterday with his counterparts from the US, the European
Community and Canada.
One western trade official immediately dismissed the Japanese trade
proposals as little more than tariff reductions already scheduled to take
place. Mr Mori said implementation of the proposal depended on 'improved
offers' from other countries, including cuts in their 'peak' tariffs.
All four ministers expressed optimism that yesterday's meeting had given the
Uruguay Round a new lease of life.
Sir Leon Brittan, the EC trade commissioner, said the talks 'achieved
everything we wanted and perhaps a little more. This meeting has increased
the rate of progress and we are now in top gear. There can be no doubt of
the momentum towards a Uruguay Round agreement.'
The ministers plan at least two more meetings in the next two months in the
hope of a breakthrough on the broad 'market access' agreement by the time
leaders of the Group of Seven industrial countries assemble for their summit
in Tokyo in July.
Mr Michael Wilson, Canada's trade minister, said the participants at
yesterday's meeting agreed to aim for a 'positive outcome' to the
long-stalled Uruguay Round this year. All four ministers declined to comment
on progress or disagreements on specific subjects.
Among the 770 products included in the Japanese offer are electronics goods,
construction and farm machinery, chemicals and rubber. Mr Mori said tariffs
on 700 of these items would be eliminated. The proposed cuts would bring the
average Japanese tariff down from 1.9 to 1.6 per cent.
The Japanese cabinet yesterday approved a Y2,188bn (Pounds 12.9bn) plan to
finance the central government's portion of the Y13,200bn emergency pump
priming package announced last month to revive the depressed Japanese
economy, Charles Leadbeater writes from Tokyo.
Most of the remainder of the package will be financed by a Y5,000bn
expansion in funds from the Fiscal Investment and Loan Programme, Japan's
shadow budget which is funded by savings deposited in the postal savings
system. The FILP funds will be used to finance an expansion in housing loans
and small business funds.
</TEXT>
