<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 93 / Finance and the Family: The Week Ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MARKS AND Spencer, the UK food and clothing retailer, is expected on Tuesday
to announce a rise in pre-tax profits from Pounds 627.2m to between Pounds
710m and Pounds 730m. The average forecast of about Pounds 725m represents
an increase of 16 per cent, but last year's figures were reduced by
exceptional redundancy costs of almost Pounds 50m. Stripping these out, the
profits increase is likely to be between 7 and 8 per cent, reflecting a
considerable pick-up in sales in the second half thanks partly to M and S's
'outstanding value' promotions.
Storehouse, which includes the BhS and Mothercare chains, should report
pre-tax profits on Thursday of about Pounds 13m to Pounds 15m, after
exceptional items. As these are mainly one-off costs relating to disposals
aimed at streamlining the business, analysts expect the City to pay more
attention to the pre-exceptional figure, forecast at Pounds 40m-Pounds 45m
(Pounds 15.8m).
Hanson, the Anglo-US conglomerate, is expected to report on Tuesday pre-tax
profits of Pounds 500m for the six months to March 31. This compares with
Pounds 488m under the old accounting rules which stripped out extraordinary
items.
Half year profits have been helped by around Pounds 25m of exceptional
profits relating to disposals, the depreciation of sterling against the
dollar and a good result from Cavenham Forest Industries in the US.
Whitbread, opening another round of brewers' results on Monday, is expected
to report pre-tax profits little changed from last year at around Pounds
222m. Volume growth for the group's beer brands is likely to be offset by
margin pressures and increased marketing expenditure; but improved first
half trading by the retail division has been maintained.
Full year results from Allied-Lyons on Tuesday should show profits up from
Pounds 610m to Pounds 618m, at the top end of market forecasts. The group's
leading spirits brands have achieved further growth and on the retailing
side, Victoria Wine and Dunkin' Donuts have had a good year.
Bass, on Wednesday, is expected to report a 5 per cent fall in interim
profits to Pounds 245m against a restated Pounds 259m. Brewing profits are
likely to show little change and retailing is still suffering from the
reduction in pub numbers. Holiday Inn profits will benefit from the upturn
in the US.
